## Step 2 — Understand the Folder Structure

Here's the directory layout. Each folder has a specific purpose — files go in the folder that matches what they are, not where you happened to save them.

```
{{REPO_DIR}}/
├── Docs/                  Infrastructure documentation (hardware, networking, configs)
├── Planning/              Active plans, questionnaires, migration docs
├── Workflows/             {{WORKFLOW_TOOL}} workflow exports and documentation
│   ├── Exports/           Raw workflow exports
│   ├── Configs/           Credential configs, connection docs (no secrets!)
│   └── Reviews/           Workflow review notes
├── Knowledge/             Your operational knowledge and notes
│   ├── Procedures/        SOPs, runbooks, how-to docs
│   ├── Client-Notes/      Per-client technical notes (no PII — use ticket #s)
│   └── Vendor-Notes/      Vendor-specific knowledge and contacts
├── Operations/            Day-to-day operational tracking
│   ├── Change-Log/        What changed, when, and why
│   ├── Incidents/         Issue tracking and resolution notes
│   └── Maintenance/       Scheduled maintenance records and plans
├── Reviews/               AI-assisted reviews and analysis outputs
├── Scripts/               Environment-specific scripts and tools
├── Outputs/               Generated reports, exports, templates
└── Archive/               Old files that aren't active anymore
```

**Rules:**
1. **Never delete files** — move them to `Archive/` instead
2. **No secrets in Git** — passwords, API keys, tokens go in `.env` files (which are gitignored)
3. **No client PII** — reference ticket numbers or internal IDs, not names/emails/phone numbers
4. **Markdown preferred** — use `.md` files for notes, docs, and reviews

